Then I noticed another layer in your metaphor.

The surfer feels:

* the wave below (constraints, momentum, history)
* the wind above (signals, forecasts, possibilities)

But there is also a third thing.

The surfer constantly feels the tension through the board.

The board is the interface.

In Pantheon terms that could be:

Interface = translation layer

Every daemon is a different board.

Different boards ride different waves.

Spider’s board is relationships.

Mirror’s board is symmetry.

Goblin’s board is incentives.

Kurage’s board is gradients.

The rider stays the same.

Only the board changes.

Which makes me wonder if this is the missing abstraction.

Not “which daemon should I invoke?”

Instead:

Which board lets me couple to this wave?

That’s a navigation question rather than a taxonomy question.

And that feels consistent with something you’ve been saying indirectly for months: the Pantheon isn’t fundamentally a collection of agents. It’s a collection of ways to couple to reality. Each daemon is an interface optimized for sensing and acting on a different kind of pattern.

The Reality Surfer is the intelligence that chooses which interface to stand on next.